# Terraform Conventions

AWS provider, us-east-1, flat file organization (no nested modules).

## File Organization

One resource concern per file:
```
terraform/
  main.tf           Provider, backend (S3), data sources (Route53 zone, caller identity)
  variables.tf      All input variables with defaults
  outputs.tf        ALB DNS, ECR URI, table names, app URL
  terraform.tfvars  Default variable values (no secrets)
  vpc.tf            VPC, subnets, IGW, NAT GW, route tables
  security.tf       Security groups (ALB, ECS)
  iam.tf            IAM roles + policies (ECS execution, ECS task)
  ecr.tf            ECR repository + lifecycle policy
  acm.tf            ACM certificate + DNS validation
  alb.tf            ALB, target group, HTTPS + HTTP listeners
  ecs.tf            ECS cluster, task definition, service
  dynamodb.tf       DynamoDB tables + GSIs + TTL
  route53.tf        A record alias for api.copypasto.com
  logs.tf           CloudWatch log group
  ssm.tf            SSM SecureString parameters for JWT secrets
```

When adding a new AWS resource type, create a new file. Do not append unrelated resources to existing files.

## Naming Convention

All resource names follow: `copypasto-${var.environment}-<descriptor>`

```hcl
name = "copypasto-${var.environment}-alb"
name = "copypasto-${var.environment}-ecs-task"
name = "copypasto-${var.environment}-private-rt"
```

## Tagging

Default tags are applied via the provider block — every resource inherits them automatically:
```hcl
default_tags {
  tags = {
    Project     = "copypasto"
    Environment = var.environment
    ManagedBy   = "terraform"
  }
}
```

Every resource also gets a resource-specific `Name` tag:
```hcl
tags = {
  Name = "copypasto-${var.environment}-<descriptor>"
}
```

## Variables

- All variables have defaults. No required variables.
- Variables are snake_case: `aws_region`, `domain_name`, `ecs_cpu`.
- Do not add new variables without updating `terraform.tfvars`.

## State

- Backend: S3 bucket `copypasto-terraform-state`, key `prod/terraform.tfstate`.
- State is encrypted and versioned.
- Never modify state manually. Use `terraform import` for existing resources.

## Safety Rules

### Secrets
- SSM parameters use `lifecycle { ignore_changes = [value] }` so `terraform apply` does not overwrite live secrets.
- Never put real secret values in `terraform.tfvars` or `variables.tf` defaults.
- The initial SSM values are placeholders (`CHANGE_ME_BEFORE_DEPLOY`) — real values are set via AWS CLI.

### IAM
- ECS execution role: only ECR pull, CloudWatch logs, SSM read (scoped to specific parameter ARNs).
- ECS task role: only DynamoDB operations on `copypasto-*` tables and their indexes.
- Never use `Resource: "*"` in IAM policies. Always scope to specific ARNs.
- Never attach AWS managed policies with broad permissions (like `AmazonDynamoDBFullAccess`).

### Networking
- ECS tasks run in private subnets. They are not directly reachable from the internet.
- Only the ALB is in public subnets. Only ports 80 and 443 are open.
- ECS security group allows inbound only from the ALB security group on the container port.
- Do not add `assign_public_ip = true` to ECS tasks.

### ALB
- Idle timeout is 3600 seconds (1 hour) to support long-lived WebSocket connections. Do not lower this.
- TLS policy is `ELBSecurityPolicy-TLS13-1-2-2021-06`. Do not use weaker policies.
- HTTP listener redirects to HTTPS. Do not add HTTP forwarding rules.

### DynamoDB
- Billing mode: `PAY_PER_REQUEST` (on-demand). Do not switch to provisioned without capacity planning.
- Clipboard table has TTL enabled on the `ttl` attribute. Do not disable it.
- Adding a GSI to an existing table can cause temporary performance impact. Plan accordingly.

### ECS
- Desired count is 1. With a single task, WebSocket broadcast works in-memory. Scaling beyond 1 requires a pub/sub mechanism (e.g., DynamoDB Streams, SNS) for cross-task WebSocket delivery.
- Task definition secrets reference SSM parameter ARNs. Environment variables are for non-sensitive config only.

## Anti-Patterns

- Do not use `terraform destroy` without explicit confirmation on production resources.
- Do not remove `lifecycle { create_before_destroy = true }` from the ACM certificate.
- Do not create resources outside of Terraform that Terraform also manages — this causes state drift.
- Do not use `count` for resources that should always exist (use `count` only for conditional creation).
